B. China
Date: Sun 10 May 2020 2:58 AM
Source: Reuters [edited]
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-china-toll/china-reports-17-more-covid-19-cases-amid-new-infections-in-wuhan-idUSKBN22N02F?il=0


Wuhan, the epicentre of the novel coronavirus [COVID-19] outbreak in China, reported on Monday [11 May 2020] its 1st cluster of infections since a lockdown on the central Chinese city was lifted a month ago [April 2020], stoking concerns of a wider resurgence of the disease. The new infections sounded a note of caution amid efforts to ease coronavirus-related restrictions across China as businesses restart and individuals go back to work.

Wuhan reported 5 new confirmed cases, all of whom live in the same residential compound. One of them was the wife of an 89-year-old male patient reported a day earlier in the 1st confirmed case in the city in more than a month. "At present, the task of epidemic prevention and control in the city is still very heavy," said the Wuhan health authority in a statement. "We must resolutely contain the risk of a rebound."

All of the latest confirmed cases were previously classified as asymptomatic, people who test positive for the virus and are capable of infecting others but do not show clinical signs such as a fever. The number of asymptomatic cases in China is not known, as they only appear on the radar of health officials when they show up positive during tests conducted as part of contact tracing and health checks.

Hundreds of asymptomatic cases in Wuhan, which was released on [8 Apr 2020] from a months-long lockdown, are currently being monitored, according to the city's health authority.

The number of new cases reported in China since April [2020] has been small compared with the thousands confirmed each day in February [2020], thanks to a nationwide regime of screening, testing, and quarantine. The government said on Friday [8 May 2020] that China will gradually reopen cinemas, museums, and other recreational venues, though restrictions including mandatory reservations and a limit on numbers will be in place.

Shanghai has already reopened some night entertainment venues such as discotheques. Walt Disney Co on Monday [11 May 2020] reopened its Shanghai Disneyland park to a reduced number of visitors.

New outbreaks in China in the past 2 months have mainly developed in residential compounds or at hospitals.

The Wuhan cases helped push the overall new COVID-19 infections confirmed on [10 May 2020] to 17, the highest daily increase since [28 Apr 2020].

Northeastern Jilin province, which on Saturday [9 May 2020] reported a cluster of infections in one of its cities, Shulan, reported 3 additional local cases. Shulan has been marked a high-risk area, the only place in China currently with that designation. "We're now in a 'war-time' mode," said Jin Hua, mayor of Shulan, which until the weekend had reported no local cases for more than 70 days.

Shulan has imposed a lockdown on its 600 000 residents since the weekend, with just one member of a household being allowed out each day to buy necessities. One of the 3 cases confirmed in the Jilin province on [10 May 2020] was from Shulan. The other 2 were from the city of Jilin uncovered through contact tracing of people who were in contact with earlier Shulan cases.

Nearby Liaoning and Heilongjiang provinces each reported one case, adding to worries about a resurgence of the outbreak in the region. A 70-year-old patient in Harbin, capital of Heilongjiang, had tested negative 7 times before results turned positive.

Of the new cases, 7 were so-called imported cases in the northern Chinese region of Inner Mongolia involving travellers from overseas.

[Bylines: Se Young Lee, Lusha Zhang, Liangping Gao, Ryan Woo; editing: Gerry Doyle, Stephen Coates, Lincoln Feast]

--
