[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 214. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the South East Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 48 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
------------------------------------------
The Americas region reported only 18 537 new cases (30.1% of the global newly reported cases), and 6830 deaths (80.3%) were recorded for this 24-hour period. It is important to mention that with the change of data source used for presenting the USA data (as mentioned in the Highlights section above), the USA has reported a total of -99 cases in the 24 hour period (in Sit Rep 111). In addition, Ecuador has reported -1480 cases in the same 24 hour period. Excluding the USA and Ecuador from the discussion and analysis, Brazil reported 55.1% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Peru at 17.9%, Mexico at 10.3%, and Canada at 7.4%.

The European region reported 25 608 new cases (41.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 1319 deaths (15.5%). Russia reported 43.0% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 15.2%, Belarus 7.3%, Turkey 6.0%, and Italy 4.2%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 9706 new cases (15.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 130 deaths (1.5%). Pakistan reported 20.5% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Saudi Arabia at 17.6%, Iran at 15.8%, Qatar at 11.6%, and Afghanistan at 8.6%.

The African region reported 2082 new cases (3.4% of the global newly reported cases) and 47 deaths (0.6%). South Africa reported 25.2% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Ghana at 12.1%, Nigeria at 11.5%, Algeria at 9.1%, Guinea-Bissau at 6.4%, and Senegal at 4.0%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1139 new cases (1.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 21 deaths (0.25%). Singapore reported 66.1% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines at 12.9%, and Japan at 10.4%. Removing Singapore from the denominator has the Philippines at 38.1%, Japan at 30.8%, Malaysia at 14.0%, and South Korea at 8.8%.

The South East Asia region reported 4506 new cases (7.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 152 deaths (1.8%). India reported 72.7% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 14.1% and Indonesia at 11.8%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 51.7% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 43.4%, the Maldives at 3.3%, and Sri Lanka at 1.0%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 10 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees too much weekend artifact and impact of reporting changes to draw any conclusions today.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
